GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 690
Short Title: The Citizens Support Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives N. Jackson, Biggs, Balkcom, and Stevens (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Judiciary 2, if favorable, State and Local Government, if favorable, Rules,
Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 3, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT DIRECTING THE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES, THE
3 DEPARTMENT OF COMMERCE, THE HOUSING FINANCE AGENCY, AND LOCAL
4 HOUSING AUTHORITIES TO DEVELOP, IMPLEMENT, AND REPORT ON A PLAN
5 TO ENSURE THAT STATE-FUNDED BENEFITS PROVIDED BY OR THROUGH
6 THESE STATE AND LOCAL AGENCIES ARE AVAILABLE ONLY TO UNITED
7 STATES CITIZENS AND NONCITIZENS RESIDING IN THE UNITED STATES WITH
8 LEGAL PERMISSION; DIRECTING STATE-FUNDED INSTITUTIONS OF HIGHER
9 EDUCATION TO ADOPT AND IMPLEMENT A POLICY TO VERIFY THAT ALL
10 APPLICANTS ARE LEGALLY AUTHORIZED TO RESIDE IN THE UNITED STATES;
11 AND DIRECTING THE DEPARTMENT OF COMMERCE, DIVISION OF
12 EMPLOYMENT SECURITY, TO ADOPT AND IMPLEMENT A POLICY TO VERIFY
13 THAT ALL APPLICANTS FOR BENEFITS ARE LEGALLY AUTHORIZED TO RESIDE
14 IN THE UNITED STATES.
15 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
16
17 PART I. DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES
18 SECTION 1. To the extent permitted by federal law, the Department of Health and
19 Human Services (DHHS) shall take all steps necessary to cease providing State-funded benefits
20 to noncitizens residing in the United States without legal permission.
21 SECTION 2. To the extent permitted by federal law, the DHHS shall develop and
22 implement a plan to review and update the eligibility criteria for all State-funded benefits to
23 ensure that noncitizens determined to be residing in the United States without legal permission
24 are ineligible to receive State-funded benefits. As a part of this plan, the DHHS shall develop a
25 method for verifying the immigration status of applicants for State-funded benefits who are
26 noncitizens prior to the initiation of benefits.
27 SECTION 3. By January 15, 2026, the DHHS shall report to the Joint Legislative
28 Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services and the Fiscal Research Division all of the
29 following:
30 (1) The steps taken to implement Section 1 of this act and the resulting success of
31 those steps.
32 (2) A list of State-funded benefits for which the DHHS is prohibited from
33 changing.
*H690-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) The plan developed and implemented pursuant to Section 2 of this act, which
2 shall include a citation to each federal law or regulation that prohibits the
3 DHHS from denying eligibility for State-funded benefits to noncitizens
4 determined to be residing in the United States without legal permission.
5 SECTION 4. As used in this Part, "State-funded benefits" includes any of the
6 following programs administered by or through a contract with the Department but excludes any
7 benefits or services available under these programs to help eligible beneficiaries access food or
8 meals:
9 (1) Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (Work First).
10 (2) Early Intervention Services.
11 (3) Rental or housing assistance programs.
12 (4) Medication assistance programs.
13 (5) Child care subsidy programs.
14 (6) Foster care and adoption assistance payments.
15 (7) Refugee assistance programs.
16 (8) Low Income Energy Assistance.
17 (9) Work First Cash Assistance and other employment and self-sufficiency
18 training and services.
19 (10) Medicaid.
20 (11) Single-stream funding.
21 (12) Inpatient psychiatric hospital services (3-Way Bed Contracts).
22 (13) The State-County Special Assistance program.
23 (14) Programs funded by the Home and Community Care Block Grant.
24 (15) Caregiver Support programs.
25
26 PART II. DEPARTMENT OF COMMERCE, HOUSING FINANCE AGENCY, AND
27 LOCAL HOUSING AUTHORITIES
28 SECTION 5. To the extent permitted by federal law, the Department of Commerce,
29 the Housing Finance Agency, and all local housing authorities established under Chapter 157 of
30 the General Statutes shall take all steps necessary to cease providing publicly funded housing
31 benefits to noncitizens residing in the United States without legal permission.
32 SECTION 6. To the extent permitted by federal law, the Department of Commerce,
33 the Housing Finance Agency, and all local housing authorities established under Chapter 157 of
34 the General Statutes shall each develop and implement a plan to review and update the eligibility
35 criteria for all publicly funded housing benefits to ensure that noncitizens determined to be
36 residing in the United States without legal permission are ineligible to receive publicly funded
37 housing benefits. As a part of this plan, the Department of Commerce, the Housing Finance
38 Agency, and all local housing authorities established under Chapter 157 of the General Statutes
39 shall develop a method for verifying the immigration status of applicants for publicly funded
40 housing benefits who are noncitizens prior to the initiation of benefits.
41 SECTION 7. By January 15, 2026, the Department of Commerce, the Housing
42 Finance Agency, and all local housing authorities established under Chapter 157 of the General
43 Statutes shall report to the Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations and the
44 Fiscal Research Division on both of the following:
45 (1) The steps taken to implement Section 5 of this act and the resulting success of
46 those steps.
47 (2) The plan developed and implemented pursuant to Section 6 of this act, which
48 shall include a citation to each federal law or regulation that prohibits the
49 Department, Office, Agency, or local government unit from denying
50 eligibility for publicly funded benefits to noncitizens determined to be
51 residing in the United States without legal permission.
Page 2 House Bill 690-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 8. As used in this Part, "publicly funded housing benefits" means any of
2 the following programs or assistance administered by or through a contract with the Department
3 of Commerce, the North Carolina Housing Finance Agency, and any local housing authority
4 established under Chapter 157 of the General Statutes:
5 (1) Community Development Block Grants (CDBG).
6 (2) Rental assistance programs.
7 (3) Transitional housing programs.
8 (4) Key Rental Assistance programs (KEY).
9 (5) Subsidized housing assistance programs.
10 (6) Housing Choice Voucher program (HCV).
11 (7) NC Home Advantage Mortgage program.
12 (8) NC 1st Home Advantage Down Payment program.
13 (9) HOME Investment Partnerships program (HOME).
14 (10) Community Living programs.
15 (11) Essential Single-Family Rehabilitation program (ESFR).
16 (12) Affordable Housing Development Fund program (AHDF)
17 (13) Emergency Solutions Grants program (ESG), including the Rapid
18 Unsheltered Survivor Housing program (RUSH).
19
20 PART III. STATE-FUNDED INSTITUTIONS OF HIGHER EDUCATION
21 SECTION 9. Notwithstanding G.S. 116-143.1 or any other provision of law, the
22 governing bodies of all institutions of higher education in North Carolina receiving State funds
23 shall adopt and implement a policy to verify, for tuition and educational benefits purposes, that
24 all applicants are legally authorized to reside in the United States.
25
26 PART IV. UNEMPLOYMENT COMPENSATION
27 SECTION 10. Notwithstanding any provision of State law and to the extent
28 permitted by federal law, the Department of Commerce, Division of Employment Security, shall
29 adopt and implement a policy to verify, for unemployment benefits purposes, that all applicants
30 are legally authorized to reside in the United States prior to the first payment of benefits.
31
32 PART V. EFFECTIVE DATE
33 SECTION 11. This act is effective when it becomes law.
